{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e7087b9a-0137-4082-b393-e63943f27da2","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what brings workloads (like `maui`) back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — re-installs workloads **at their current versions**. It fixes corrupted installations but won't pull newer versions needed by an updated SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:** SDK moved forward → workloads need to catch up → `dotnet workload update`.\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf it still fails after that, run `dotnet workload list` to confirm the `maui` workload is installed, then rebuild.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3a46158b-233d-47ba-8543-b8c291327c62","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":252},"id":"47485621-003f-4cdd-8e61-1c1ec719ef7e","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:45:02.154Z","parentId":"61308df2-fafb-4371-808f-531a2e7b983e"}
